	<text>
		<body>
				<p rend="align(center)">THE &#39;OMER</p>
				<p>Is not his a beautiful day&#63; Look out&#33; the sun is shining clear<lb/>ly with the mild rays of spring&#44; and sends not down the scorch&#45;<lb/>ing beams which compel us in the summer to seek a shelter again<lb/> his oppressive heat. Everything invites us to go abroad and<lb/> enjoy the balmy spring.</p>
				<p>Yet do we not wander abroad in the field to enjoy awakened<lb/> nature and why&#63; we felt ourselves called upon to enter our<lb/> house of worship in accordance with the custom of our fathers&#44;<lb/> to celebrate this <sic>econd</sic> day of the festival of our redep frm<lb/> <placeName>Egypt</placeName>. &#8212;&#8212;&#8212;</p>
				<p>We may assume the <date>Passover</date> to be the period of our early man&#45;<lb/>hood&#44; when the age of childhood and youth are already past.<lb/> &#8212;So was out education as a people in <placeName>Egypt</placeName>. We went there in<lb/> the boyhood of our nationality&#44; and in the iron furnace of<lb/> <del>ntion</del> we were taught to look up to our eternal Saviour<lb/> for enlargement as all the gods of men&#39;s invention are helpless<lb/> themselves&#44; without power to understand the Almighty&#39;s fiat.</p>
				<p>As it is with nations so is it with individuals&#59;<lb/> The Psalmist says out days on earth are seventy years&#44; and<lb/> rarely reach eighty&#44; &#59; experience proves the correctness<lb/> of this ancient statement &#8212;&#8212; we lose the elasticity<lb/> of our steps&#44; the vigor of our limbs&#44; the light of our eyes<lb/> is dimmed&#44; nay our intellect&#44; perhaps&#44; becomes uncertain and<lb/> vague&#44; and those on whose advice nations <sic>depnded</sic>&#44; those who<lb/> moved pub <sic>assmbls</sic> by their fervent <sic>eloq</sic>&#44; the poets who<lb/> charmed multitudes by the sweetness of their <sic>nukbers</sic>&#44;<lb/> musicians whose tuneful strains have become the delight of<lb/> the world <sic>arenow</sic> mere <sic>shdws</sic> of <sic>thr</sic> <sic>forn</sic> selves&#45; &#8212;the<lb/> picture is sad &#38; depressing&#44; it is what awaits us all&#59; we<lb/> cannot avoid the pangs of <sic>dises</sic> or the terrors of dissolution&#44;<lb/> they tower up before us in the dim but certain distance&#44; and<lb/> neither craven fear nor daring indifference can ward off what</p>
				<p rend="Footnote.">The proof down to this <sic>wrd</sic> was sent to <persName>Mr. Leeser</persName> on <date>Dec28&#44;<lb/> 1867</date>&#44; but he never <sic>recoverd</sic> <sic>suffcient</sic> strength to complete<lb/> the writing of the sermon. A few days after the receipt of<lb/> the proof he wrote on it the following&#44; which he intended for<lb/> the printer. It was found among his papers after his death&#58;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">&#8220;I tried yesterday to write&#44; and succeeded in jotting</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">down about twenty lines&#59; but I find I must wait a <sic>littk</sic></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">longer. There shall be no useless delay. I feel</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">easier&#44; but suffer greatly.&#8221;</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">L.</persName></p>
				<p>The twenty lines have not been found.</p>
				<p>Deliv Beth El <date>secnd Pass</date> <date>5618</date> or <date>5619</date>.</p>
